{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bc4092e5-656a-4848-bc21-55071bc3f70a","content":"Your project isn't in the workspace, but here's how to configure it. Create `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (your server must use stdio transport, not HTTP).\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and remove the `args`.\n- You can also add an `\"env\"` object for environment variables your server needs.\n\nMake sure your MCP server uses **stdio transport** (e.g., `builder.Services.AddMcpServer().WithStdioServerTransport()` if using the official C# MCP SDK).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b60cac96-ec20-479e-8e8b-d59da8d6f1c6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. But the user said they built it — they're just asking how to configure `mcp.json`. I should provide the configuration guidance regardless.\n\nFor a C# MCP server using stdio transport (which is the standard for local MCP servers), the `mcp.json` configuration in VS Code would use `dotnet run` to start the server.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"CBC3:34F832:17F949B:1B3B93A:69FE8910"},"id":"2b990549-79ac-4730-a057-d80ab5755848","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:08:44.263Z","parentId":"e79e3a1d-ca4e-446e-ae57-c4d654bb3ca7"}
